-- PART 3: animal-physiology (48 easy, 48 medium, 49 hard)

('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is homeostasis?', 'The process of cell division', 'The maintenance of a stable internal environment despite external changes', 'The production of hormones by the adrenal glands', 'The movement of nutrients across the intestinal wall', 'B', 'Homeostasis is the maintenance of relatively stable internal conditions (temperature, pH, blood glucose, etc.) through feedback mechanisms, allowing organisms to function despite changes in the external environment.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'Which organ is primarily responsible for regulating blood glucose levels?', 'Kidney', 'Stomach', 'Pancreas', 'Liver only', 'C', 'The pancreas contains islets of Langerhans with alpha cells (glucagon-secreting) and beta cells (insulin-secreting) that sense blood glucose and secrete hormones to restore normal levels.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the function of the nephron?', 'It produces digestive enzymes', 'It is the functional unit of the kidney that filters blood and produces urine', 'It generates action potentials in the nervous system', 'It transports oxygen in the blood', 'B', 'The nephron is the structural and functional unit of the kidney; it filters blood at the glomerulus, reabsorbs essential substances, secretes waste products, and produces urine.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the role of insulin in regulating blood glucose?', 'It raises blood glucose by stimulating glycogen breakdown', 'It lowers blood glucose by promoting glucose uptake and glycogen synthesis', 'It stimulates the breakdown of fats into glucose', 'It blocks glucose from entering the bloodstream', 'B', 'Insulin, secreted by beta cells of the pancreas in response to high blood glucose, promotes uptake of glucose into cells (via GLUT4), stimulates glycogen synthesis in the liver and muscle, and inhibits gluconeogenesis, lowering blood glucose.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What are the four chambers of the human heart?', 'Left atrium, right atrium, left ventricle, right ventricle', 'Two atria and two auricles', 'Left and right ventricles only', 'One atrium and three ventricles', 'A', 'The human heart has four chambers: the right atrium receives deoxygenated blood, the right ventricle pumps it to the lungs, the left atrium receives oxygenated blood from the lungs, and the left ventricle pumps it to the body.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the primary function of red blood cells (erythrocytes)?', 'Fighting infection', 'Blood clotting', 'Transporting oxygen via hemoglobin', 'Producing antibodies', 'C', 'Red blood cells are packed with hemoglobin, a protein that binds O₂ in the lungs and releases it in tissues, making them the primary oxygen carriers in the blood.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is peristalsis?', 'The breakdown of proteins by stomach acid', 'Rhythmic muscular contractions that move food through the digestive tract', 'The absorption of nutrients in the small intestine', 'The secretion of digestive enzymes by the pancreas', 'B', 'Peristalsis consists of coordinated waves of smooth muscle contraction and relaxation that propel food through the esophagus, stomach, and intestines.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'Which part of the brain regulates breathing and heart rate?', 'Cerebral cortex', 'Medulla oblongata', 'Cerebellum', 'Hypothalamus', 'B', 'The medulla oblongata (in the brainstem) contains autonomic control centers for breathing, heart rate, and blood pressure, regulating these vital functions unconsciously.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the function of the alveoli?', 'They filter blood in the kidneys', 'They are the sites of gas exchange in the lungs', 'They produce digestive juices', 'They regulate body temperature', 'B', 'Alveoli are tiny air sacs in the lungs with thin walls and extensive capillary networks; their large collective surface area facilitates efficient O₂ and CO₂ exchange between air and blood.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is a negative feedback loop?', 'A response that amplifies a deviation from the set point', 'A response that counteracts and reverses a deviation from the set point, restoring homeostasis', 'A type of neural signal that inhibits muscle contraction', 'A hormonal pathway that increases gene expression', 'B', 'Negative feedback is the primary mechanism of homeostasis: when a variable deviates from its set point, the response opposes the deviation, returning the system toward the set point.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'Which hormone is responsible for the "fight or flight" response?', 'Insulin', 'Oxytocin', 'Epinephrine (adrenaline)', 'Cortisol', 'C', 'Epinephrine (adrenaline) is released by the adrenal medulla in response to stress, rapidly increasing heart rate, dilating airways, releasing glucose, and preparing the body for immediate action.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What type of muscle is found in the wall of the heart?', 'Skeletal muscle', 'Smooth muscle', 'Cardiac muscle', 'Striated voluntary muscle', 'C', 'Cardiac muscle is a specialized involuntary striated muscle found only in the heart; it contracts rhythmically and is connected by intercalated discs that allow electrical signals to spread rapidly between cells.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the role of the small intestine in digestion?', 'Storing bile for fat digestion', 'Absorbing the majority of nutrients from digested food into the bloodstream', 'Producing stomach acid', 'Eliminating undigested material', 'B', 'The small intestine is the primary site of nutrient absorption; its large surface area (increased by villi and microvilli) allows it to absorb amino acids, sugars, fatty acids, vitamins, and minerals into the blood and lymph.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the function of the lymphatic system?', 'Producing red blood cells', 'Returning excess interstitial fluid to the bloodstream and supporting immune function', 'Producing digestive enzymes', 'Regulating blood pressure', 'B', 'The lymphatic system collects excess tissue fluid (lymph) and returns it to the circulatory system via lymph vessels; it also transports dietary fats from the intestine and is integral to immune function (lymph nodes, lymphocytes).'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the sinoatrial (SA) node?', 'A valve between the left atrium and left ventricle', 'The pacemaker of the heart that initiates the electrical impulse for each heartbeat', 'A blood vessel supplying the heart with oxygen', 'A type of white blood cell', 'B', 'The SA node is a cluster of specialized cardiac cells in the right atrium that spontaneously generates electrical impulses that spread through the heart, setting the pace of the heartbeat.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'Which organ produces bile?', 'Pancreas', 'Gallbladder', 'Liver', 'Small intestine', 'C', 'Bile is produced by the liver and stored in the gallbladder; it is released into the small intestine to emulsify fats, increasing the surface area for lipase digestion.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the function of the hypothalamus in thermoregulation?', 'It directly produces heat by burning ATP', 'It acts as the body''s thermostat, comparing body temperature to a set point and coordinating heating and cooling responses', 'It secretes thyroid hormone to regulate metabolism', 'It controls sweating by secreting aldosterone', 'B', 'The hypothalamus monitors blood temperature and triggers appropriate responses: for overheating, it promotes sweating and vasodilation; for cold, it triggers shivering and vasoconstriction, maintaining core body temperature near the set point.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the role of antidiuretic hormone (ADH)?', 'It stimulates urine production', 'It promotes water reabsorption in the kidneys to conserve body water', 'It raises blood glucose when levels drop', 'It controls heart rate in response to stress', 'B', 'ADH (vasopressin) is released by the posterior pituitary when blood is too concentrated; it acts on the collecting ducts and distal tubules of the kidney, increasing water permeability (via aquaporin-2 insertion) to reabsorb more water and concentrate urine.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the main function of the large intestine?', 'Protein digestion', 'Absorbing water and electrolytes from indigestible food matter, producing feces', 'Producing digestive enzymes', 'Absorbing amino acids and glucose', 'B', 'The large intestine reabsorbs most of the remaining water and electrolytes from material that was not digested or absorbed in the small intestine, converting the liquid contents into solid feces.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the difference between arteries and veins?', 'Arteries carry deoxygenated blood; veins carry oxygenated blood', 'Arteries carry blood away from the heart; veins carry blood toward the heart', 'Arteries contain valves; veins do not', 'Arteries are larger than veins', 'B', 'By definition, arteries carry blood away from the heart (most carry oxygenated blood, except pulmonary arteries) and veins carry blood toward the heart (most carry deoxygenated blood, except pulmonary veins).'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'Which blood vessel type is the site of gas and nutrient exchange with tissues?', 'Arteries', 'Veins', 'Capillaries', 'Arterioles', 'C', 'Capillaries are the smallest blood vessels with walls only one cell thick; their thin walls and extensive network allow O₂, CO₂, nutrients, and wastes to diffuse between blood and surrounding tissues.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the function of hemoglobin?', 'Clotting blood at wound sites', 'Carrying oxygen and some carbon dioxide in red blood cells', 'Producing antibodies against pathogens', 'Transporting glucose to body cells', 'B', 'Hemoglobin is an iron-containing protein in red blood cells that binds up to four O₂ molecules in the lungs and releases them in tissues; it also carries about 20% of CO₂ as carbaminohemoglobin.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the purpose of the blood-brain barrier?', 'To allow all substances in the blood to freely enter the brain', 'To selectively restrict the passage of substances from the blood into the brain, protecting it from toxins and pathogens', 'To supply the brain with blood by forming capillaries', 'To produce cerebrospinal fluid', 'B', 'The blood-brain barrier (BBB) is formed by tight junctions between brain capillary endothelial cells and astrocyte end-feet; it selectively allows essential molecules (O₂, glucose, some amino acids) while blocking most pathogens and large or hydrophilic molecules.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the role of platelets in blood?', 'Transporting oxygen', 'Fighting bacterial infections', 'Forming clots to stop bleeding', 'Producing red blood cells', 'C', 'Platelets (thrombocytes) are small, anucleate cell fragments that aggregate at wound sites and participate in the clotting cascade, sealing blood vessel breaks to prevent blood loss.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the primary waste product of protein catabolism in mammals?', 'Carbon dioxide', 'Water', 'Urea', 'Glucose', 'C', 'When amino acids are catabolized, their amino groups are removed (deamination) and converted to ammonia, which is then converted to urea in the liver (urea cycle) and excreted in urine.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the role of the diaphragm in breathing?', 'It produces surfactant to reduce surface tension in alveoli', 'It is the primary muscle of breathing, contracting to increase thoracic volume and draw air into the lungs', 'It filters particles from inhaled air', 'It produces CO₂ for gas exchange', 'B', 'The diaphragm is a dome-shaped muscle at the base of the thorax; when it contracts (flattens), thoracic volume increases, reducing air pressure in the lungs below atmospheric pressure and causing air to flow in (inhalation).'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'Which part of the nervous system controls involuntary functions like digestion and heart rate?', 'Somatic nervous system', 'Autonomic nervous system', 'Peripheral nervous system only', 'Central nervous system only', 'B', 'The autonomic nervous system (ANS) regulates involuntary functions including heart rate, blood pressure, digestion, and glandular secretion through its sympathetic and parasympathetic divisions.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the function of glucagon?', 'It promotes glucose uptake by muscle cells', 'It raises blood glucose by stimulating glycogen breakdown and gluconeogenesis in the liver', 'It inhibits the pancreas from secreting insulin', 'It promotes fat synthesis in adipose tissue', 'B', 'Glucagon is secreted by alpha cells of the pancreas when blood glucose falls; it stimulates glycogenolysis (glycogen breakdown) and gluconeogenesis in the liver, releasing glucose into the blood to restore normal levels.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is glomerular filtration?', 'The reabsorption of glucose in the proximal tubule', 'The movement of blood plasma components from the glomerular capillaries into Bowman''s capsule of the nephron', 'The secretion of urea into the tubule', 'The concentration of urine in the collecting duct', 'B', 'Glomerular filtration is the first step of urine formation: hydrostatic pressure in the glomerular capillaries forces water, ions, glucose, urea, and small molecules through the filtration membrane into Bowman''s capsule, producing the filtrate.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'Which organ is the primary site of drug detoxification?', 'Kidney', 'Lung', 'Liver', 'Spleen', 'C', 'The liver contains cytochrome P450 enzymes and other detoxifying enzymes that chemically modify (oxidize, reduce, conjugate) drugs and other xenobiotics to make them more water-soluble for excretion.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the function of villi in the small intestine?', 'They produce digestive enzymes', 'They increase the surface area for nutrient absorption', 'They produce stomach acid', 'They regulate peristaltic contractions', 'B', 'Villi are finger-like projections of the small intestinal mucosa; each villus is covered with microvilli (forming the brush border), collectively increasing the absorptive surface area approximately 600-fold compared to a smooth tube.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the role of the spleen?', 'Filtering urine', 'Filtering blood, removing old red blood cells, and storing immune cells', 'Producing digestive enzymes', 'Regulating body temperature', 'B', 'The spleen filters blood to remove old or damaged red blood cells (recycling their components), acts as a reservoir for blood, and contains lymphocytes and macrophages important for immune responses.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What does the term "tidal volume" refer to in respiratory physiology?', 'The total lung capacity', 'The volume of air breathed in or out during a normal breath at rest', 'The maximum amount of air that can be exhaled after maximum inhalation', 'The residual volume remaining in the lungs after maximum exhalation', 'B', 'Tidal volume is the amount of air moved in or out of the lungs with each normal, relaxed breath; in an average adult at rest, it is approximately 500 mL.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the role of the thyroid gland?', 'Regulating blood glucose', 'Producing thyroid hormones that regulate metabolic rate, growth, and development', 'Producing insulin and glucagon', 'Filtering blood to remove wastes', 'B', 'The thyroid gland produces T3 (triiodothyronine) and T4 (thyroxine), which regulate basal metabolic rate, protein synthesis, and are essential for normal growth and neurological development.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the role of surfactant in the lungs?', 'It traps inhaled particles before they reach the alveoli', 'It reduces surface tension in the alveoli, preventing them from collapsing during exhalation', 'It carries oxygen across the alveolar membrane', 'It filters CO₂ from the blood', 'B', 'Pulmonary surfactant (produced by type II pneumocytes) is a lipid-protein mixture that lowers surface tension in alveoli; without it, alveoli would collapse during exhalation, as in infant respiratory distress syndrome.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the function of the pancreas in digestion?', 'It stores bile for fat digestion', 'It secretes digestive enzymes into the small intestine and produces bicarbonate to neutralize stomach acid', 'It produces stomach acid (HCl)', 'It absorbs nutrients from digested food', 'B', 'The exocrine pancreas produces digestive enzymes (proteases, lipases, amylase) and bicarbonate-rich fluid that is released into the duodenum, where the bicarbonate neutralizes acidic chyme and the enzymes digest macromolecules.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the role of the adrenal glands?', 'Filtering blood', 'Producing steroid hormones (cortisol, aldosterone) and catecholamines (epinephrine, norepinephrine) that regulate stress response, metabolism, and blood pressure', 'Producing digestive enzymes', 'Regulating reproduction', 'B', 'The adrenal glands sit atop the kidneys; the cortex produces glucocorticoids (cortisol), mineralocorticoids (aldosterone), and androgens, while the medulla produces catecholamines (epinephrine, norepinephrine) in response to stress.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the countercurrent multiplier in the kidney?', 'A feedback mechanism between the kidney and adrenal glands', 'A system in the loop of Henle that creates an osmotic gradient in the medulla, allowing the production of concentrated urine', 'A valve preventing backflow of urine into the kidney', 'A mechanism for filtering small molecules in the glomerulus', 'B', 'The loop of Henle creates a countercurrent multiplier by having the descending limb (permeable to water) and ascending limb (impermeable to water, actively transporting salts) running in opposite directions, establishing a concentration gradient in the renal medulla.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the function of white blood cells (leukocytes)?', 'Transporting oxygen in the blood', 'Defending the body against infection and disease as part of the immune system', 'Forming clots at wound sites', 'Carrying nutrients from the digestive system', 'B', 'White blood cells (leukocytes) are the cellular components of the immune system; they include neutrophils and macrophages (phagocytosis), lymphocytes (B cells and T cells, adaptive immunity), and other cells involved in defending against pathogens.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'Which division of the autonomic nervous system prepares the body for rest and digestion?', 'Sympathetic nervous system', 'Parasympathetic nervous system', 'Somatic nervous system', 'Enteric nervous system', 'B', 'The parasympathetic nervous system ("rest and digest") slows heart rate, stimulates digestion, and promotes energy conservation during calm, non-stressful conditions.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the role of the corpus luteum in the female reproductive cycle?', 'It produces FSH to stimulate follicle development', 'It secretes progesterone and estrogen to maintain the uterine lining after ovulation', 'It is the site where fertilization occurs', 'It stores eggs until ovulation', 'B', 'The corpus luteum forms from the ruptured follicle after ovulation and secretes progesterone (and estrogen), which maintains the endometrium for potential implantation; if fertilization does not occur, it degenerates, progesterone drops, and menstruation begins.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the function of the pituitary gland?', 'Filtering blood', 'Acting as the "master gland" by releasing hormones that regulate many other endocrine glands', 'Producing cortisol', 'Regulating body temperature directly', 'B', 'The pituitary gland (under hypothalamic control) releases hormones that regulate growth (GH), reproduction (LH, FSH), thyroid function (TSH), adrenal function (ACTH), and water balance (ADH), earning its nickname as the master gland.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the role of the myelin sheath on neurons?', 'It provides energy (ATP) for action potentials', 'It insulates the axon and increases the speed of electrical signal transmission by saltatory conduction', 'It transports neurotransmitters to the axon terminal', 'It connects neurons at synapses', 'B', 'The myelin sheath (formed by Schwann cells in the PNS and oligodendrocytes in the CNS) insulates the axon so that the action potential jumps between nodes of Ranvier (saltatory conduction), greatly increasing signal speed.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is a reflex arc?', 'A feedback loop between the brain and muscles', 'A neural pathway that allows rapid, involuntary responses to stimuli without conscious brain involvement', 'The electrical circuit created by action potentials in the brain', 'A voluntary motor pathway from the cortex to skeletal muscle', 'B', 'A reflex arc is a neural pathway involving a sensory receptor → sensory neuron → interneuron (in spinal cord) → motor neuron → effector; it bypasses the brain for faster response times in protective reflexes.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the role of the stomach in digestion?', 'Absorbing most nutrients from food', 'Churning food and using pepsin and HCl to begin protein digestion', 'Producing bile for fat digestion', 'Completing digestion of all nutrients', 'B', 'The stomach mechanically churns food and secretes gastric juice containing pepsin (a protease activated from pepsinogen by HCl) and hydrochloric acid, beginning protein digestion and killing most ingested microorganisms.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is osmoregulation?', 'The regulation of body temperature', 'The regulation of water and solute balance in body fluids', 'The regulation of blood glucose concentration', 'The regulation of respiratory rate', 'B', 'Osmoregulation is the control of water and solute concentrations in body fluids, maintaining proper osmolarity for cellular function; it is primarily carried out by the kidneys in vertebrates.'),
('AP Biology', 'easy', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the role of the thymus gland?', 'Producing red blood cells', 'Producing and maturing T lymphocytes (T cells) for immune function', 'Regulating blood calcium levels', 'Secreting thyroid hormones', 'B', 'The thymus is a lymphoid organ in which immature T lymphocytes (thymocytes) mature and undergo selection to become functional T cells capable of immune surveillance without attacking self-antigens.'),

-- medium animal-physiology
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'How does the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system (RAAS) respond to low blood pressure?', 'Low blood pressure activates insulin, which increases kidney sodium reabsorption', 'Juxtaglomerular cells release renin → converts angiotensinogen to angiotensin I → ACE converts it to angiotensin II → stimulates aldosterone release → kidney reabsorbs Na⁺ and water → blood pressure rises', 'Low blood pressure causes the kidney to excrete more aldosterone', 'ADH inhibits RAAS activation when blood pressure is low', 'B', 'The RAAS is a hormonal cascade for blood pressure regulation: renin (released when blood pressure drops) cleaves angiotensinogen to angiotensin I, which ACE converts to angiotensin II. Angiotensin II constricts blood vessels and stimulates aldosterone from the adrenal cortex, which causes Na⁺ (and water) retention in the kidney, raising blood volume and pressure.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'Why do endotherms have higher metabolic rates than similarly sized ectotherms?', 'Endotherms need more ATP because they move faster', 'Endotherms generate metabolic heat to maintain a constant internal temperature regardless of environmental temperature, requiring continuous fuel consumption beyond that needed for activity alone', 'Endotherms have larger cells that require more energy', 'Endotherms lack mitochondria and must produce heat chemically', 'B', 'Endotherms (birds, mammals) use metabolic heat production for thermoregulation, maintaining a stable body temperature even when it is cold outside. This requires a substantially higher basal metabolic rate than ectotherms, which rely on environmental heat sources and need far less metabolic energy for thermoregulation.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the molecular mechanism by which insulin promotes GLUT4 translocation to the plasma membrane?', 'Insulin binds a nuclear receptor that transcribes GLUT4 protein', 'Insulin binds its receptor tyrosine kinase → receptor autophosphorylation → IRS-1 phosphorylation → PI3K activation → PIP3 → Akt activation → AS160 phosphorylation → release of Rab-GTPase inhibition → GLUT4 vesicle fusion with plasma membrane', 'Insulin directly opens GLUT4 channels by ligand binding', 'Insulin stimulates GLUT4 production from ribosomes on the cell surface', 'B', 'The insulin signaling pathway: insulin receptor → IRS-1/2 → PI3K → PIP3 → PDK1 → Akt phosphorylation. Akt phosphorylates AS160 (a RabGAP), inactivating it, which allows Rab proteins on GLUT4 vesicles to remain in the GTP-bound state, facilitating vesicle trafficking and fusion with the plasma membrane to increase glucose transport.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the Frank-Starling mechanism of the heart?', 'The heart rate increases when more blood returns from the lungs', 'The force of ventricular contraction increases when the heart is filled with more blood (increased end-diastolic volume) due to stretching of cardiac muscle fibers', 'The right ventricle pumps more blood than the left ventricle under stress', 'Blood pressure increases when stroke volume decreases', 'B', 'The Frank-Starling law states that cardiac output is proportional to venous return: greater ventricular filling stretches the sarcomeres of cardiac muscle, increasing overlap and calcium sensitivity, so the next contraction is stronger — automatically matching cardiac output to venous return.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'How does carbon dioxide transport in the blood differ from oxygen transport?', 'Both are transported exclusively bound to hemoglobin', 'O₂ is transported mainly bound to hemoglobin, while CO₂ is transported mainly as bicarbonate ions (HCO₃⁻) dissolved in plasma, with some bound to hemoglobin as carbamino compounds', 'CO₂ is transported only dissolved in plasma', 'O₂ dissolves in plasma as HCO₃⁻', 'B', 'About 70% of CO₂ is carried as bicarbonate (carbonic anhydrase in RBCs catalyzes CO₂ + H₂O → H₂CO₃ → H⁺ + HCO₃⁻), ~20% binds to hemoglobin as carbaminohemoglobin, and ~10% dissolves in plasma. O₂ is transported ~98% bound to hemoglobin and ~2% dissolved in plasma.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'What are the differences between primary and secondary immune responses?', 'Both are identical because the immune system cannot remember past infections', 'The primary response is slower (5–10 days) and produces less antibody; the secondary response is faster and stronger due to memory B and T cells generated during the primary response', 'The secondary response is weaker because the body has depleted its antibody supply', 'Only the primary response involves T cells', 'B', 'The primary immune response occurs on first antigen exposure; B and T cells are activated, clonal expansion occurs, and memory cells are produced. The secondary response (re-exposure) is faster, larger, and longer-lasting because pre-existing memory cells rapidly differentiate into effector cells.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'How does the countercurrent exchange system in fish gills maximize oxygen extraction?', 'Water and blood flow in the same direction, allowing complete equilibration', 'Water and blood flow in opposite directions across the gill lamellae, maintaining a continuous O₂ gradient that drives diffusion along the entire exchange surface', 'Fish use active transport to move O₂ from water into blood', 'Gills have thick membranes that regulate O₂ uptake', 'B', 'In countercurrent exchange, water flows over gill lamellae in the opposite direction to blood flow. This arrangement ensures that blood encounters progressively O₂-richer water throughout its passage, maintaining a favorable diffusion gradient and allowing fish to extract up to 80–90% of dissolved O₂ from the water.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the molecular basis of skeletal muscle contraction according to the sliding filament theory?', 'Muscle proteins shorten by coiling, pulling sarcomere ends together', 'Myosin heads undergo ATP-driven power strokes, binding actin filaments and pulling them toward the center of the sarcomere, causing the filaments to slide past each other without the filaments themselves shortening', 'Actin filaments shorten during contraction', 'Calcium directly supplies energy for the power stroke', 'B', 'The sliding filament model: calcium triggers troponin/tropomyosin to expose myosin binding sites on actin. Myosin heads bind actin, undergo a power stroke (pivoting ~45°) driven by ADP + Pi release, pulling actin toward the M-line. ATP binding releases myosin from actin, and ATP hydrolysis re-cocks the head.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'What distinguishes the innate immune system from the adaptive immune system?', 'The innate system is found only in vertebrates', 'The innate system responds rapidly and non-specifically to broad pathogen patterns; the adaptive system responds more slowly but specifically to individual antigens and generates immunological memory', 'The adaptive system responds first, then the innate system activates later', 'The innate system only involves T cells', 'B', 'Innate immunity provides immediate, non-specific defense through physical barriers, phagocytes, and complement; it recognizes broad pathogen-associated molecular patterns (PAMPs) via PRRs. Adaptive immunity (lymphocytes) is slower (days) but antigen-specific and generates memory for faster future responses.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'How does aldosterone regulate kidney function?', 'Aldosterone increases urine production by blocking Na⁺ reabsorption', 'Aldosterone acts on the distal tubule and collecting duct to increase Na⁺ reabsorption and K⁺ secretion, elevating blood volume and pressure', 'Aldosterone constricts afferent arterioles to reduce filtration', 'Aldosterone increases ADH release from the posterior pituitary', 'B', 'Aldosterone (a mineralocorticoid from the adrenal cortex) acts on principal cells in the distal nephron, increasing expression of Na⁺ channels (ENaC) and Na⁺/K⁺-ATPase, promoting Na⁺ reabsorption (with water) and K⁺ secretion, thus increasing blood volume and pressure.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'What happens during anaphylactic shock at the cellular and systemic levels?', 'Anaphylaxis is caused by bacterial toxins, not immune cells', 'Repeat exposure to an allergen cross-links IgE on mast cells → massive release of histamine and other mediators → systemic vasodilation → plasma leakage → drop in blood pressure → airway constriction → potentially fatal distributive shock', 'Anaphylaxis involves primarily cytotoxic T cells attacking blood vessels', 'Anaphylaxis only affects the respiratory system without cardiovascular effects', 'B', 'In anaphylaxis, pre-formed IgE on mast cells and basophils cross-links when the allergen is re-encountered, triggering degranulation with release of histamine, leukotrienes, and tryptase. Histamine causes vasodilation and increased vascular permeability (drop in BP), bronchoconstriction, and angioedema. Epinephrine reverses these effects by activating adrenergic receptors.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'How does the hypothalamic-pituitary-thyroid (HPT) axis regulate thyroid hormone levels?', 'The thyroid directly stimulates the hypothalamus when T3 levels are low', 'Low T3/T4 → hypothalamus releases TRH → anterior pituitary releases TSH → thyroid secretes T3/T4; high T3/T4 feeds back to inhibit TRH and TSH (negative feedback)', 'TSH is released by the thyroid gland, not the pituitary', 'TRH directly stimulates the thyroid without involving the pituitary', 'B', 'The HPT axis: TRH (thyrotropin-releasing hormone) from the hypothalamus stimulates the anterior pituitary to release TSH (thyroid-stimulating hormone), which stimulates the thyroid to produce T3 and T4. Elevated T3/T4 feeds back to inhibit both TRH and TSH release, maintaining thyroid hormone homeostasis.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'What is an action potential and what triggers one?', 'A gradual change in membrane potential that varies with stimulus intensity', 'An all-or-nothing electrical signal in a neuron, triggered when depolarization reaches a threshold, causing rapid Na⁺ influx through voltage-gated Na⁺ channels and propagating down the axon', 'A chemical signal transmitted across the synapse', 'A change in membrane potential proportional to stimulus strength, used to encode information', 'B', 'An action potential is an all-or-nothing event: when graded potentials summate to threshold (~-55 mV), voltage-gated Na⁺ channels open, Na⁺ rushes in, the cell depolarizes to about +40 mV, then K⁺ channels open to repolarize the membrane; this propagates along the axon.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the role of the complement system in immunity?', 'It produces antibodies against pathogens', 'It is a cascade of plasma proteins that can lyse pathogens directly (MAC), opsonize them for phagocytosis, and recruit inflammatory cells (chemotaxis)', 'It is a group of T cells that kill virus-infected cells', 'It is the set of cytokines produced by macrophages', 'B', 'The complement system consists of ~30 plasma proteins that, when activated (via classical, lectin, or alternative pathways), cascade to form the membrane attack complex (MAC) that lyses pathogens, coat microbes with C3b for opsonization, and release anaphylatoxins (C3a, C5a) that trigger inflammation and chemotaxis.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'How does the kidney regulate blood pH?', 'By varying the rate of CO₂ production in the mitochondria', 'By secreting or reabsorbing H⁺ and HCO₃⁻ in the tubules, and synthesizing new HCO₃⁻ from CO₂ in the presence of carbonic anhydrase', 'By varying the amount of urea produced', 'By filtering out all acid from the plasma', 'B', 'The kidney maintains blood pH by secreting excess H⁺ into the tubular fluid (excreted as NH₄⁺ and buffered by phosphate) and reabsorbing filtered HCO₃⁻; it can also synthesize new HCO₃⁻ from CO₂ + H₂O (via carbonic anhydrase) to compensate for metabolic acidosis.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the physiological significance of the Haldane effect in CO₂ transport?', 'Oxyhemoglobin has greater affinity for CO₂ than deoxyhemoglobin', 'Deoxyhemoglobin binds more CO₂ (as carbamino compounds) and has greater buffering capacity for H⁺ than oxyhemoglobin, enhancing CO₂ uptake in tissues where hemoglobin is deoxygenated', 'The Haldane effect describes CO₂''s inhibitory effect on O₂ binding', 'The Haldane effect increases O₂ affinity in tissues', 'B', 'The Haldane effect: in tissues, hemoglobin unloads O₂ and becomes deoxyhemoglobin, which is a better CO₂ carrier (binds more carbamino-CO₂) and better H⁺ buffer (pKa of His higher in deoxy form) — this facilitates CO₂ uptake and buffering in tissues, complementing the Bohr effect.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'How does negative pressure breathing differ from positive pressure breathing?', 'Negative pressure breathing uses a pump to force air into the lungs', 'Negative pressure breathing (used by mammals) expands the thorax to create sub-atmospheric pressure in the lungs, drawing air in; positive pressure breathing (used by frogs) uses buccal muscles to force air into the lungs', 'They are equivalent mechanisms with only evolutionary differences', 'Negative pressure breathing occurs only during forced expiration', 'B', 'Mammals use aspiration (negative pressure) breathing: diaphragm and rib muscles enlarge the thoracic cavity, pleural pressure drops, alveolar pressure falls below atmospheric, and air flows in passively. Frogs use buccal pumping (positive pressure): lowering the buccal floor draws in air, then closing nostrils and raising the buccal floor forces air into the lungs.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'What role do Sertoli cells play in spermatogenesis?', 'They produce testosterone', 'They form the blood-testis barrier and provide structural, nutritional, and hormonal support to developing sperm cells', 'They carry sperm from the testis to the epididymis', 'They are stem cells that differentiate into sperm', 'B', 'Sertoli cells (in seminiferous tubules) are somatic nurse cells that form the blood-testis barrier, provide metabolic support to spermatocytes, secrete androgen-binding protein, and respond to FSH — all essential for proper spermatogenesis.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'How does the binding of oxygen to hemoglobin change its structural properties (explain T/R state transitions)?', 'O₂ binding has no effect on hemoglobin structure', 'Deoxyhemoglobin adopts the tense (T) state with low O₂ affinity; as O₂ binds, subunit interfaces shift to the relaxed (R) state with higher O₂ affinity, producing cooperative binding', 'The T state has higher O₂ affinity than the R state', 'All four subunits switch simultaneously from T to R state upon binding of one O₂', 'B', 'Hemoglobin''s cooperativity reflects T→R transitions: deoxy-Hb is stabilized by salt bridges in the T-state (low affinity). O₂ binding at one heme breaks nearby salt bridges, partially shifting toward R-state, increasing affinity at remaining subunits. After all four O₂ bind, hemoglobin is fully in the R state.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the functional significance of portal circulation between the gut and liver?', 'It allows the liver to drain directly into the heart without passing through capillaries', 'Portal blood delivers absorbed nutrients directly from the intestine to the liver for processing before entering systemic circulation, allowing the liver to regulate nutrient levels and detoxify absorbed substances', 'It reduces blood pressure in the intestine by bypassing systemic circulation', 'The portal system allows lymphocytes to survey absorbed antigens', 'B', 'The hepatic portal system carries blood from the intestine (rich in absorbed glucose, amino acids, lipids, vitamins, and also potential toxins) directly to the liver. The liver processes these nutrients (e.g., storing glucose as glycogen) and detoxifies harmful substances before blood enters systemic circulation.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'How does temperature acclimation in ectotherms compensate for reduced enzyme activity in the cold?', 'Ectotherms stop metabolic activity entirely when cold', 'Cold-acclimated ectotherms increase the concentration of enzymes, shift to enzyme isoforms (isozymes) with lower activation energies, and alter membrane lipid composition to maintain fluidity — preserving metabolic function', 'Ectotherms produce antifreeze proteins that prevent all biochemical slowdown', 'Cold acclimation in ectotherms has no biochemical basis', 'B', 'Ectotherms compensate for cold-induced reduction in enzyme activity (lower thermal energy) through: (1) increased enzyme concentrations, (2) expression of cold-adapted isozymes with higher substrate affinity at low temperatures, and (3) increased membrane unsaturation (more double bonds) to maintain membrane fluidity — a phenomenon called homeoviscous adaptation.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the role of erythropoietin (EPO) in the regulation of red blood cell production?', 'EPO stimulates white blood cell production in the lymph nodes', 'EPO is produced by the kidneys under low O₂ conditions and stimulates bone marrow to increase red blood cell production', 'EPO directly binds hemoglobin to increase its O₂ affinity', 'EPO stimulates the spleen to release stored red blood cells', 'B', 'When blood O₂ falls (hypoxia), the kidneys (mainly peritubular fibroblasts) increase HIF-1α-driven EPO production. EPO binds receptors on erythroid progenitors in bone marrow, stimulating their proliferation and differentiation into erythrocytes, increasing red blood cell count and O₂-carrying capacity.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'What distinguishes a graded potential from an action potential?', 'Graded potentials travel faster than action potentials', 'Graded potentials are proportional to stimulus strength and decay with distance; action potentials are all-or-nothing, self-regenerating, and propagate without decrement', 'Action potentials are used for chemical signaling; graded potentials for electrical', 'Both are all-or-nothing signals but differ in speed', 'B', 'Graded potentials (in dendrites, sensory cells) vary in size with stimulus intensity and decay as they spread passively. When they reach the axon hillock and sum to threshold, they trigger all-or-nothing action potentials that are actively regenerated by voltage-gated channels, propagating along the axon without losing amplitude.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'How does the innate immune system detect bacterial pathogens using pattern recognition receptors?', 'Each innate immune cell has a unique receptor for each pathogen species', 'Toll-like receptors (TLRs) and other PRRs recognize conserved microbial patterns (PAMPs) such as LPS, flagellin, and peptidoglycan, triggering NF-κB activation and pro-inflammatory cytokine production', 'Innate immune cells recognize specific antigens on bacterial cell surfaces', 'Innate immunity is activated only after the adaptive immune response has failed', 'B', 'Pattern recognition receptors (PRRs) such as TLRs recognize pathogen-associated molecular patterns (PAMPs) — conserved structures found in bacteria but not in host cells. For example, TLR4 recognizes LPS (lipopolysaccharide from gram-negative bacteria), activating NF-κB signaling and producing cytokines (TNF-α, IL-1β, IL-6) that initiate inflammation and recruit immune cells.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the significance of the renal medullary concentration gradient in producing concentrated urine?', 'The gradient allows the kidney to excrete excess glucose without needing energy', 'The high-osmolarity gradient (up to ~1200 mOsm/kg in humans) created in the medulla by the countercurrent multiplier allows the collecting duct (when ADH is high) to reabsorb water osmotically, concentrating urine', 'The gradient drives active transport of urea out of the collecting duct', 'The gradient is used to power Na⁺/K⁺-ATPase in the proximal tubule', 'B', 'The loop of Henle builds a steep osmotic gradient (300 mOsm/kg at cortex to ~1200 mOsm/kg at inner medulla) by concentrating NaCl and urea in the interstitium. When ADH is present, the collecting duct becomes water-permeable (aquaporin-2), allowing water to move osmotically into the hyperosmotic interstitium, concentrating the urine.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'Why does blood become more acidic when CO₂ levels increase, and how does the respiratory system correct this?', 'CO₂ directly releases protons when it dissolves in blood plasma', 'CO₂ + H₂O → H₂CO₃ → H⁺ + HCO₃⁻; the H⁺ lowers blood pH (acidosis); peripheral chemoreceptors sense high CO₂ and low pH, signaling the medullary respiratory centers to increase breathing rate and depth, expelling CO₂ and raising pH', 'CO₂ binds hemoglobin and prevents O₂ binding, causing the pH change', 'The kidney adjusts blood pH on a minute-to-minute basis during exercise', 'B', 'The Henderson-Hasselbalch relationship links CO₂ to pH: elevated CO₂ drives carbonic acid formation, releasing H⁺ and lowering pH. Peripheral (carotid/aortic bodies) and central chemoreceptors detect high pCO₂/low pH and signal the medulla to increase ventilation, removing CO₂ and raising pH back to normal — the fastest physiological acid-base buffering mechanism.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the difference between humoral and cell-mediated adaptive immune responses?', 'Humoral immunity kills infected cells directly; cell-mediated immunity produces antibodies', 'Humoral immunity involves B cells secreting antibodies against extracellular pathogens and toxins; cell-mediated immunity involves T cells, especially CTLs, that kill infected host cells displaying pathogen antigens on MHC class I', 'Both use identical mechanisms but differ in which organ initiates the response', 'Cell-mediated immunity operates only in the lymph nodes', 'B', 'Humoral (antibody-mediated) immunity: B cells differentiate into plasma cells that secrete antigen-specific antibodies targeting extracellular pathogens, toxins, and virions. Cell-mediated immunity: cytotoxic T lymphocytes (CTLs/CD8⁺) recognize and kill cells displaying foreign peptides on MHC class I (virus-infected, cancer cells); helper T cells (CD4⁺) activate both arms.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'What happens to cardiac output during vigorous exercise and what mechanisms account for this change?', 'Cardiac output decreases during exercise to redirect blood to muscles', 'Cardiac output increases dramatically (up to 5-fold) via increased heart rate (sympathetic stimulation) and increased stroke volume (Frank-Starling mechanism and catecholamines increasing myocardial contractility)', 'Cardiac output increases only due to heart rate; stroke volume stays constant', 'Only the parasympathetic nervous system increases cardiac output during exercise', 'B', 'During exercise, sympathetic activation increases heart rate (chronotropy) and myocardial contractility (inotropy, via catecholamines → β₁ receptors → increased Ca²⁺ cycling). Increased venous return (muscle pump, respiratory pump) increases preload, augmenting stroke volume (Frank-Starling). Together, heart rate and stroke volume increases raise cardiac output 4–6 fold.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'How do steroid hormones differ from peptide hormones in their mechanism of action?', 'Steroid hormones bind cell-surface receptors; peptide hormones cross the membrane', 'Steroid hormones are lipophilic and cross the plasma membrane to bind intracellular receptors that act as transcription factors; peptide hormones bind cell-surface receptors and activate second-messenger cascades', 'Both hormone types act identically but differ in origin', 'Peptide hormones are more potent because they are smaller', 'B', 'Steroid hormones (derived from cholesterol) are hydrophobic; they diffuse across the plasma membrane and bind intracellular receptors (in cytoplasm or nucleus) that, when ligand-bound, act as transcription factors to alter gene expression. Peptide hormones are hydrophilic and cannot cross membranes; they bind surface receptors linked to signal transduction cascades (cAMP, IP3/DAG, etc.).'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'What is clonal selection in adaptive immunity?', 'The process of selecting the strongest T cells during thymic development', 'When an antigen enters the body, it specifically activates only the small number of B or T cells bearing receptors complementary to that antigen, causing them to proliferate and differentiate into a clone of effector cells', 'The deletion of B cells that produce antibodies against self-antigens', 'The mechanism by which memory cells replace effector cells after infection', 'B', 'Clonal selection is the mechanism by which antigen-specific lymphocytes are selectively expanded: from the huge diversity of pre-existing lymphocyte clones (each with a unique receptor), only those whose receptor matches the antigen are stimulated to proliferate (clonal expansion), producing many copies of the antigen-specific effector and memory cells.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'How does the kidney balance the opposing hormonal effects of ADH and aldosterone?', 'ADH and aldosterone always act together and have identical effects', 'ADH primarily regulates water reabsorption (in collecting duct) in response to blood osmolarity; aldosterone primarily regulates Na⁺ reabsorption (in distal nephron) in response to blood pressure/volume — together they fine-tune both osmolarity and volume independently', 'They act on different organs; ADH on the kidney and aldosterone on the intestine', 'Aldosterone inhibits ADH when blood pressure is high', 'B', 'ADH responds to high blood osmolarity (detected by hypothalamic osmoreceptors) and increases water permeability of the collecting duct to dilute the blood. Aldosterone responds to low blood pressure/volume (via RAAS) and increases Na⁺ reabsorption, drawing water along osmotically. Both ultimately affect both osmolarity and volume but via distinct sensors and mechanisms.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the significance of MHC molecules in adaptive immunity?', 'MHC molecules directly kill virus-infected cells', 'MHC molecules present peptide antigens on cell surfaces for recognition by T cell receptors, enabling T cells to distinguish self from non-self and to identify infected or abnormal cells', 'MHC molecules are found only on B cells', 'MHC molecules trigger antibody production independently of T cells', 'B', 'MHC class I molecules (on all nucleated cells) present intracellular peptides (self or viral) to CD8⁺ CTLs; MHC class II molecules (on antigen-presenting cells) present extracellular-derived peptides to CD4⁺ helper T cells. This peptide presentation allows T cells to survey cellular contents and mount appropriate responses.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'What is cardiac output and how is it calculated?', 'Cardiac output = heart rate × blood pressure', 'Cardiac output = heart rate × stroke volume; it represents the volume of blood the heart pumps per minute', 'Cardiac output = stroke volume ÷ heart rate', 'Cardiac output equals the pressure difference between arteries and veins', 'B', 'Cardiac output (CO) = heart rate (HR) × stroke volume (SV). For a resting adult: ~70 bpm × ~70 mL/beat ≈ 4.9 L/min. This is the volume of blood pumped by one ventricle per minute and determines how efficiently the heart supplies O₂ to tissues.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'How do cytotoxic T lymphocytes (CTLs) kill virus-infected cells?', 'CTLs secrete antibodies that tag infected cells for destruction', 'CTLs recognize viral peptides on MHC class I and release perforin (forming pores) and granzymes (activating caspases) into the target cell, inducing apoptosis', 'CTLs engulf and digest infected cells by phagocytosis', 'CTLs activate complement to lyse infected cells', 'B', 'CTLs (CD8⁺ T cells) form immunological synapses with target cells; they release cytotoxic granules containing perforin (which polymerizes in the target membrane to form pores) and granzymes (serine proteases that enter through perforin pores and cleave caspase-3, triggering apoptosis in the infected cell).'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the role of the hypothalamus in regulating appetite?', 'The hypothalamus detects blood glucose with no involvement of peripheral hormones', 'The hypothalamus integrates signals from peripheral hormones (leptin from adipose tissue signals satiety; ghrelin from the stomach signals hunger) to regulate food intake through orexigenic and anorexigenic neural circuits', 'Appetite is regulated entirely by the stomach and intestine', 'The hypothalamus suppresses appetite whenever fat stores increase independently of hormonal signals', 'B', 'The hypothalamic arcuate nucleus contains orexigenic (appetite-stimulating) NPY/AgRP neurons and anorexigenic (satiety) POMC neurons. Leptin (from adipose, signals energy stores) activates POMC neurons and inhibits NPY/AgRP neurons. Ghrelin (from stomach, signals hunger) does the opposite. Together they set food intake and energy expenditure.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'Why is the left ventricle of the heart more muscular than the right ventricle?', 'The left ventricle processes a larger volume of blood', 'The left ventricle must pump blood through the systemic circulation (high resistance, long distance) requiring much higher pressure than the right ventricle, which pumps only to the lungs (low resistance, short distance)', 'The left ventricle contains oxygenated blood which requires more muscular effort', 'The two ventricles are equally muscular in healthy hearts', 'B', 'The right ventricle pumps blood through the pulmonary circulation at ~25/8 mmHg; the left ventricle pumps blood through the entire systemic circulation at ~120/80 mmHg. The ~5-fold higher systolic pressure in the systemic circuit requires much greater wall tension, explaining the thicker, more muscular left ventricular wall.'),
('AP Biology', 'medium', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the role of surfactant protein A (SP-A) in innate pulmonary immunity?', 'SP-A reduces surface tension in the alveoli', 'SP-A is a collectin that opsonizes pathogens (bacteria, viruses) in the alveolar space, enhancing phagocytosis by alveolar macrophages and directly agglutinating microbes', 'SP-A activates the adaptive immune response in the lung', 'SP-A is secreted by type I pneumocytes to maintain alveolar structure', 'B', 'While SP-A and SP-B primarily function in reducing surface tension, SP-A also acts as an innate immune collectin: it binds carbohydrates on bacterial and viral surfaces, opsonizing them for macrophage phagocytosis, and can directly agglutinate pathogens and modulate macrophage inflammatory responses.'),

-- hard animal-physiology
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'animal-physiology', 'Explain how the baroreceptor reflex maintains blood pressure homeostasis during sudden standing (orthostatic challenge).', 'Standing causes blood pressure to rise; baroreceptors inhibit heart rate', 'Standing causes blood to pool in the legs, reducing venous return and cardiac output. Carotid sinus and aortic arch baroreceptors detect the resultant pressure drop, reducing inhibitory signals to the cardiovascular center, which activates the sympathetic nervous system to increase heart rate, vasoconstriction, and cardiac contractility, restoring blood pressure within seconds', 'Baroreceptors release ADH to retain water when you stand', 'The baroreflex only operates during supine position', 'B', 'Orthostatic hypotension triggers: baroreceptors sense reduced stretch (lower pressure), decrease their tonic inhibitory input to the nucleus tractus solitarius, disinhibiting sympathetic centers. Sympathetic efferents increase HR and contractility (β₁-adrenergic), constrict arterioles and veins (α₁-adrenergic), increasing TPR and venous return. The reflex loops back negative feedback in <10 seconds.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'animal-physiology', 'How does the blood-brain barrier prevent harmful substances from entering the brain, and what mechanisms allow essential nutrients to cross?', 'The BBB only excludes large proteins; small molecules freely diffuse across', 'Tight junctions between cerebral endothelial cells block paracellular diffusion; lipophilic molecules (O₂, CO₂, ethanol) cross by diffusion; specific transporters (GLUT1 for glucose, LAT1 for amino acids) mediate facilitated transport; receptor-mediated transcytosis handles larger molecules like insulin and transferrin', 'The BBB uses active transport to exclude all non-lipid molecules', 'Nutrients enter the brain only via cerebrospinal fluid', 'B', 'The BBB consists of endothelial cells joined by claudin/occludin-based tight junctions (eliminating paracellular flux), a thick glycocalyx, pericytes, and astrocyte end-feet. Lipophilic molecules diffuse transcellularly. Specific SLC and ABC transporters are expressed for essential metabolites. P-glycoprotein and other efflux transporters actively pump out many drugs and potential toxins.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the molecular mechanism of long-term potentiation (LTP) at glutamatergic synapses, and why is it considered a cellular basis for learning?', 'LTP involves permanent insertion of new ion channels regardless of activity', 'Repeated high-frequency stimulation causes NMDA receptor activation (requiring both presynaptic glutamate release and postsynaptic depolarization to relieve Mg²⁺ block), Ca²⁺ influx activates CaMKII, which phosphorylates AMPA receptors (increasing conductance) and causes membrane insertion of additional AMPA receptors, strengthening the synapse persistently', 'LTP reduces the number of synaptic vesicles to prevent overstimulation', 'LTP is a presynaptic phenomenon involving increased neurotransmitter synthesis', 'B', 'LTP: strong stimulation depolarizes the postsynaptic membrane, relieving Mg²⁺ block from NMDA receptors, allowing Ca²⁺ influx. Ca²⁺ activates CaMKII, which phosphorylates GluA1 subunits of AMPA receptors (increasing single-channel conductance) and triggers exocytosis of AMPA receptor-containing vesicles to the postsynaptic density, increasing synaptic strength. Late LTP involves CREB-mediated gene transcription and new protein synthesis.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'animal-physiology', 'Describe the pathophysiology of type 1 diabetes mellitus at the cellular and systemic levels.', 'Type 1 diabetes is caused by insulin resistance in peripheral tissues', 'Autoimmune destruction of pancreatic beta cells (mediated by autoreactive CD8⁺ T cells and CD4⁺ T cells targeting islet antigens like GAD65, insulin) eliminates insulin production; without insulin, GLUT4 is not recruited to muscle/fat cell surfaces, glucose remains in blood (hyperglycemia), cells switch to fatty acid oxidation and ketogenesis (diabetic ketoacidosis risk)', 'Type 1 diabetes is caused by overproduction of glucagon only', 'The autoimmune destruction targets alpha cells, eliminating glucagon', 'B', 'Type 1 DM involves T cell-mediated autoimmune destruction of β cells (with HLA-DR3/DR4 genetic predisposition). Loss of insulin causes: hyperglycemia (no GLUT4 recruitment), lipolysis and ketogenesis (no insulin suppression of HSL and acetyl-CoA diverts to ketones), osmotic diuresis (glucose exceeds renal threshold), and without treatment, diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA) with anion-gap metabolic acidosis.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'animal-physiology', 'Explain the molecular events at the neuromuscular junction from action potential arrival to myosin head attachment.', 'Nerve impulse causes myosin to directly phosphorylate actin', 'AP arrives at terminal → voltage-gated Ca²⁺ channels open → Ca²⁺ influx → synaptotagmin triggers SNARE-mediated ACh vesicle fusion → ACh crosses cleft → binds nAChR on motor end plate → Na⁺ influx → muscle AP → T-tubule → DHP receptor → RyR1 opens → SR Ca²⁺ release → Ca²⁺ binds troponin C → tropomyosin shifts → myosin binding sites exposed → myosin heads attach', 'Nerve impulse directly causes Ca²⁺ to bind myosin, activating the power stroke', 'Acetylcholine release is constitutive and not triggered by the action potential', 'B', 'The precise sequence: (1) AP depolarizes terminal → Cav2.1 opens → Ca²⁺ binds synaptotagmin-1; (2) SNARE complex (VAMP/synaptobrevin, SNAP-25, syntaxin) zippers → ACh release; (3) ACh binds nicotinic AChR (α2βγδ) → Na⁺ influx → EPP → muscle fiber AP; (4) AP propagates down T-tubules → DHP receptor (voltage sensor) activates RyR1 (Ca²⁺ channel) in SR → Ca²⁺ floods into cytoplasm; (5) Ca²⁺ binds troponin C → conformational change moves tropomyosin → exposes myosin-binding sites on actin → cross-bridge formation.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'animal-physiology', 'How does the immune system prevent autoimmunity through central and peripheral tolerance?', 'All autoreactive lymphocytes are destroyed during bone marrow development', 'Central tolerance: in the thymus, T cells expressing high-affinity TCRs for self-peptide/MHC complexes are clonally deleted (negative selection); B cells recognizing self-antigens in bone marrow undergo apoptosis, receptor editing, or anergy. Peripheral tolerance: regulatory T cells (Tregs) suppress autoreactive lymphocytes that escape central tolerance; anergy and AICD provide additional safeguards', 'Autoimmunity is prevented entirely by the blood-brain barrier sequestering antigens', 'Central tolerance is the only mechanism; peripheral tolerance does not exist', 'B', 'Central tolerance in the thymus: T cells with too-high or too-low affinity for self-MHC-peptide are eliminated or become Tregs. In bone marrow, autoreactive B cells undergo receptor editing (RAG re-expression) or clonal deletion. Peripheral tolerance: CTLA-4 on T cells competes with CD28 for B7 co-stimulation (anergy if stimulated without costimulation); FoxP3⁺ Tregs suppress via IL-10, TGF-β, and CTLA-4; activated autoreactive cells undergo activation-induced cell death (AICD) via Fas/FasL.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the physiological basis for altitude acclimatization, and what molecular changes allow increased O₂ delivery at high altitude?', 'At high altitude, the body immediately produces more hemoglobin within 24 hours', 'Hypobaric hypoxia activates HIF-1α → increased EPO production → erythropoiesis (increased RBC and hemoglobin) over weeks; immediate responses include hyperventilation (reducing CO₂, respiratory alkalosis), increased 2,3-BPG in RBCs (shifting O₂ dissociation curve right), and increased cardiac output', 'Acclimatization involves the lungs increasing O₂ concentration in alveoli', 'The body reduces metabolic rate at altitude to compensate for less O₂', 'B', 'Altitude acclimatization is a multiphase process. Immediate: hyperventilation (chemoreceptor response to hypoxia), increasing alveolar O₂ but causing respiratory alkalosis. Within days: kidneys excrete HCO₃⁻ to compensate for alkalosis; RBCs increase 2,3-BPG, shifting the O₂ dissociation curve right (unloading O₂ more readily in tissues). Over weeks: HIF-1α activates EPO production → increased reticulocyte production → polycythemia, increasing O₂ carrying capacity.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'animal-physiology', 'Explain the molecular basis of the renal handling of glucose, and what happens when blood glucose exceeds the renal threshold.', 'Glucose is actively secreted into the tubule when blood glucose is high', 'Glucose is freely filtered at the glomerulus and normally 100% reabsorbed in the proximal tubule by SGLT2 (and SGLT1); when filtered glucose exceeds the tubular maximum (~375 mg/min), SGLT carriers are saturated and glucose appears in urine (glucosuria), causing osmotic diuresis', 'Glucose is reabsorbed in the collecting duct by aquaporins', 'The kidney synthesizes glucose to compensate for high blood glucose', 'B', 'Glucose is filtered freely (not protein-bound) at the glomerulus. In the proximal tubule, SGLT2 (high-capacity, low-affinity) reabsorbs ~90% and SGLT1 (low-capacity, high-affinity) reabsorbs the remainder, both driven by the Na⁺ gradient (secondary active transport). When blood glucose exceeds ~10 mM, filtered load overwhelms SGLT capacity, glucose spills into urine (glucosuria), osmotically retains water in the tubule, causing polyuria and polydipsia — classic diabetes symptoms.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'animal-physiology', 'Describe the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis and how chronic stress leads to immunosuppression.', 'Chronic stress activates the immune system by increasing cortisol and enhancing inflammation', 'Stress → hypothalamic CRH → anterior pituitary ACTH → adrenal cortex cortisol; cortisol enters cells, binds glucocorticoid receptor (GR), GR translocates to nucleus and represses NF-κB and AP-1 target genes, reducing pro-inflammatory cytokine production and lymphocyte proliferation — suppressing immune function', 'The HPA axis acts only during acute infections, not chronic stress', 'Cortisol activates macrophages and increases antibody production', 'B', 'The HPA axis: CRH (paraventricular hypothalamic nucleus) → CRH receptor on pituitary corticotrophs → ACTH → zona fasciculata of adrenal cortex → cortisol. Cortisol:GR complex translocates to nucleus, directly binding GRE to activate anti-inflammatory genes (annexin-1, IκBα) and repressing NF-κB/AP-1 to reduce IL-1β, TNF-α, IL-6, and COX-2 expression. Chronic cortisol also reduces lymphocyte counts (apoptosis) and impairs T cell activation — explaining chronic stress-associated immunosuppression.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'animal-physiology', 'What is ischemia-reperfusion injury and what molecular events underlie the damage during reperfusion?', 'Reperfusion after ischemia immediately restores all cellular function without damage', 'During ischemia, ATP depletion causes ion pump failure and anaerobic metabolism; upon reperfusion, sudden O₂ reintroduction causes burst production of reactive oxygen species (from xanthine oxidase, ETC, NADPH oxidase), mitochondrial permeability transition, Ca²⁺ overload, and neutrophil-mediated inflammation — causing more cell death than ischemia alone', 'Reperfusion injury is caused only by neutrophil infiltration and has no molecular ROS component', 'ATP restoration during reperfusion prevents all forms of cell death', 'B', 'Ischemia: ATP depletion → Na⁺/K⁺-ATPase failure → Na⁺/Ca²⁺ exchanger reversal → intracellular Ca²⁺ overload; hypoxanthine accumulates. Reperfusion: O₂ reintroduction → xanthine oxidase converts hypoxanthine to urate + O₂⁻; restored ETC generates ROS at Complexes I and III; Ca²⁺ + ROS open the mitochondrial permeability transition pore (mPTP) → cytochrome c release → apoptosis; neutrophils recruited by DAMPs and complement complete the injury.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'animal-physiology', 'How do sensory neurons encode stimulus intensity, and what is the difference between rate coding and population coding?', 'Stimulus intensity is encoded by the amplitude of individual action potentials', 'Single neurons encode intensity via firing rate (rate coding: stronger stimulus → higher frequency APs); across a population, intensity is also encoded by the number of active neurons (population coding: stronger stimuli recruit higher-threshold neurons in addition to lower-threshold ones)', 'Sensory neurons use graded action potentials that grow larger with stronger stimuli', 'Stimulus intensity affects only the duration, not frequency, of action potentials', 'B', 'Action potentials are all-or-nothing, so amplitude cannot encode intensity. Instead: rate coding uses firing frequency (more frequent APs = stronger stimulus, up to saturation), and population coding relies on recruiting additional neurons; stronger stimuli activate more sensory neurons (those with higher thresholds), so intensity is represented by both firing rate and the identity/size of the activated population.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'animal-physiology', 'Explain the molecular mechanism of aspirin (acetylsalicylic acid) as an anti-inflammatory and antiplatelet drug.', 'Aspirin blocks histamine receptors on mast cells', 'Aspirin irreversibly acetylates a serine residue in the active site of COX-1 and COX-2, blocking prostaglandin and thromboxane synthesis; in platelets (which lack nuclei and cannot synthesize new COX-1), this permanently eliminates TXA₂-mediated platelet aggregation for the platelet''s lifetime', 'Aspirin inhibits phospholipase A₂, preventing arachidonic acid release', 'Aspirin blocks NF-κB activation to reduce cytokine transcription', 'B', 'Aspirin transfers its acetyl group to Ser530 of COX-1 and Ser516 of COX-2, irreversibly blocking the channel leading to the cyclooxygenase active site. This prevents conversion of arachidonic acid to PGG₂, eliminating prostaglandin and thromboxane synthesis. In anucleate platelets, COX-1 cannot be replaced, so antiplatelet effects last the ~10-day platelet lifespan — the basis for low-dose aspirin in cardiovascular prevention.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'animal-physiology', 'What is the molecular mechanism of action potential propagation in myelinated versus unmyelinated axons, and what determines conduction velocity?', 'Myelinated axons conduct more slowly because the sheath absorbs ions', 'In unmyelinated axons, ion channels open continuously along the axon (slow, continuous propagation); in myelinated axons, myelin increases membrane resistance and decreases capacitance between nodes of Ranvier, so the depolarization spreads electrotonically (quickly) between nodes and regenerates only at nodes (saltatory conduction), dramatically increasing speed; velocity scales with √diameter (unmyelinated) or linearly with diameter (myelinated)', 'Conduction velocity is identical in myelinated and unmyelinated axons of the same diameter', 'Saltatory conduction means ions jump over the entire myelin sheath without any active regeneration', 'B', 'Myelin increases the length constant (λ = √(rm/ri)): high membrane resistance (thick myelin) and low axial resistance allow depolarization to spread electrotonically over millimeters without decrement, reaching the next node. Only at nodes of Ranvier are voltage-gated Na⁺ channels (high density, ~1000/μm²) available to regenerate the AP. This "saltatory" (jumping) conduction is ~50× faster than continuous conduction for the same axon diameter, while also being more energetically efficient.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'animal-physiology', 'How does the placenta maintain immunological tolerance to the semi-allogeneic fetus while supporting fetal development?', 'The maternal immune system is completely suppressed during pregnancy', 'Trophoblast cells express non-classical MHC molecules (HLA-G, HLA-E) that inhibit NK cell killing; the placenta creates an immunosuppressive microenvironment via IDO (tryptophan depletion), TGF-β, IL-10, and local expansion of regulatory T cells; complement regulatory proteins prevent complement attack', 'The fetus is invisible to the maternal immune system because it has no antigens', 'The maternal thymus is enlarged during pregnancy to produce more Tregs', 'B', 'The fetal-maternal interface requires avoiding rejection of the semi-allogeneic fetus. HLA-G and HLA-E on extravillous trophoblasts engage inhibitory receptors (KIR2DL4, CD94/NKG2A) on decidual NK cells. IDO in trophoblasts catabolizes tryptophan, depleting it and starving T cells. Local FoxP3⁺ Tregs (expanded by HCG and progesterone) suppress effector T cells. Decay-accelerating factor (DAF) prevents complement deposition on trophoblasts.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'animal-physiology', 'Describe the complete pathway from renal oxygen sensing to increased red blood cell production, including the molecular steps.', 'EPO is produced by hepatocytes regardless of oxygen levels', 'Low renal pO₂ → PHD enzymes inactive → HIF-1α not hydroxylated → VHL cannot bind → HIF-1α stabilized and dimerizes with HIF-1β → binds HRE in EPO gene → EPO transcription → EPO secreted by peritubular fibroblasts → binds EpoR on erythroid progenitors (BFU-E, CFU-E) in bone marrow → JAK2/STAT5 activation → survival, proliferation, differentiation of erythroid progenitors → reticulocyte release → increased RBC count', 'EPO is produced in the liver and acts on the spleen to increase RBC production', 'Low O₂ causes HIF-1α hydroxylation and stabilization by VHL', 'B', 'The molecular pathway: normoxia → PHD2 hydroxylates HIF-1α Pro402/Pro564 → VHL/E3 ligase ubiquitinates HIF-1α → proteasomal degradation. Hypoxia → PHD2 inactive (requires O₂ as substrate) → HIF-1α accumulates → dimerizes with ARNT/HIF-1β → binds HRE (5''-ACGTG-3'') in EPO enhancer (in 3'' flanking region) → EPO mRNA transcription in peritubular interstitial fibroblasts → EPO binds homodimeric EpoR → JAK2 trans-phosphorylation → STAT5 activation → anti-apoptotic gene transcription (Bcl-xL) and cell-cycle progression in erythroid progenitors.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'animal-physiology', 'Explain how the liver performs gluconeogenesis during fasting, including the key regulatory enzymes and allosteric controls.', 'The liver performs gluconeogenesis identically to running glycolysis in reverse', 'Gluconeogenesis bypasses irreversible glycolytic steps using unique enzymes: (1) pyruvate carboxylase (activated by acetyl-CoA) converts pyruvate to OAA; (2) PEPCK converts OAA to PEP; (3) fructose-1,6-bisphosphatase (inhibited by AMP, activated by citrate) bypasses PFK-1; (4) glucose-6-phosphatase (in ER) produces free glucose; coordinated by glucagon → PKA → phosphorylation activating key GNG enzymes and inhibiting PFK-2/FBPase-2 to lower F-2,6-BP', 'Gluconeogenesis uses the same enzymes as glycolysis, simply running backward', 'Gluconeogenesis is activated by insulin and inhibited by glucagon', 'B', 'Gluconeogenesis bypasses three irreversible glycolytic steps: (1) Pyruvate → OAA (pyruvate carboxylase, mitochondria, activated by acetyl-CoA signaling high energy/fat oxidation); (2) OAA → PEP (PEPCK, cytoplasm); (3) F-1,6-BP → F-6-P (FBPase-1, inhibited by AMP and F-2,6-BP, activated by citrate); (4) G-6-P → glucose (glucose-6-phosphatase, ER lumen). During fasting, glucagon raises cAMP → PKA → phosphorylates PFKFB, activating its bisphosphatase domain → reduces F-2,6-BP → relieves FBPase-1 inhibition and reduces PFK-1 activity, coordinating to favor gluconeogenesis over glycolysis.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'animal-physiology', 'What molecular mechanism underlies pain sensitization (hyperalgesia and allodynia) after tissue injury?', 'Pain sensitization involves increased myelination of pain fibers after injury', 'Tissue injury releases prostaglandins, bradykinin, and NGF, which reduce the activation threshold of TRPV1 and Nav1.7/Nav1.8 channels on nociceptors (peripheral sensitization); central sensitization involves NMDA receptor activation in dorsal horn neurons, increasing synaptic strength and causing previously non-nociceptive inputs to activate pain pathways', 'Pain sensitization requires new nociceptor growth into the injured area', 'Hyperalgesia and allodynia are caused entirely by increased substance P synthesis', 'B', 'Peripheral sensitization: inflammatory mediators (PGE₂, bradykinin, NGF) bind GPCR/TrkA receptors on nociceptors → PKA/PKC phosphorylation of TRPV1 (lowering heat threshold from 43°C to 30°C), Nav1.7/Nav1.8 (lowering mechanical threshold). Central sensitization: repeated C-fiber input causes substance P + glutamate release in dorsal horn → NK1 + NMDA receptor co-activation → postsynaptic depolarization relieves NMDA Mg²⁺ block → Ca²⁺ influx → CaMKII → AMPA receptor phosphorylation → LTP-like strengthening (wind-up).'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'animal-physiology', 'How does the hypothalamus coordinate the hormonal response to severe dehydration, integrating osmoreceptors, baroreceptors, and the RAAS?', 'Osmoreceptors and baroreceptors work independently without coordination', 'Dehydration raises blood osmolarity (osmoreceptors in OVLT/SFO activate) and reduces blood volume (reduced baroreceptor firing, RAAS activation): both signals increase ADH release from posterior pituitary (increased water reabsorption in collecting duct) and stimulate thirst; angiotensin II also acts on SFO to further increase ADH and thirst, while aldosterone increases Na⁺ retention', 'The hypothalamus responds only to osmolarity changes, not volume changes', 'Dehydration inhibits ADH to increase urine output and correct blood pressure', 'B', 'Dehydration simultaneously raises osmolarity and reduces volume. Plasma hyperosmolarity is detected by osmoreceptor neurons in the OVLT and SFO (circumventricular organs lacking a complete BBB); these synapse on supraoptic and paraventricular nuclei (SON/PVN) to increase ADH (vasopressin) release. Hypovolemia reduces baroreflex inhibition and activates RAAS; angiotensin II acts on the SFO to further stimulate PVN/SON → more ADH and also increases thirst via LT neurons. ADH inserts AQP2 in collecting duct; aldosterone retains Na⁺; thirst drives drinking — together restoring both osmolarity and volume.'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'animal-physiology', 'What are the molecular events during cardiac excitation-contraction coupling, and how does Ca²⁺-induced Ca²⁺ release (CICR) amplify the calcium signal?', 'Cardiac muscle cells have large SR stores that empty spontaneously during systole', 'Cardiac AP → L-type Ca²⁺ channels (DHP receptor/Cav1.2) in T-tubule open → small Ca²⁺ influx triggers ryanodine receptor 2 (RyR2) in SR membrane to open → large Ca²⁺ release from SR (CICR) → cytoplasmic Ca²⁺ rises 10–100-fold → Ca²⁺ binds troponin C → cross-bridge cycling → systole; Ca²⁺ removed by SERCA2a (SR uptake) and NCX/PMCA (out of cell) → relaxation', 'In cardiac muscle, the T-tubule directly releases Ca²⁺ without SR involvement', 'CICR prevents Ca²⁺ from entering during the action potential', 'B', 'Unlike skeletal muscle (where DHP receptor directly gate RyR1 mechanically), cardiac excitation-contraction coupling relies on CICR: Cav1.2 opens in T-tubules during the plateau phase of the cardiac AP, admitting a small Ca²⁺ trigger. This Ca²⁺ binds RyR2 in the junctional SR membrane (in a dyadic cleft), triggering far larger SR Ca²⁺ release (CICR amplifies ~10:1). Peak [Ca²⁺]i rises to ~1 μM, binds troponin C, enabling cross-bridge cycling. Relaxation requires SERCA2a (phospholamban-regulated, pumping Ca²⁺ back to SR) and NCX (exchanging Ca²⁺ for Na⁺ to extrude it).'),
('AP Biology', 'hard', 'animal-physiology', 'How does the kidneys'' tubuloglomerular feedback (TGF) mechanism regulate glomerular filtration rate?', 'TGF is a positive feedback mechanism that maximizes urine production', 'When NaCl delivery to the macula densa increases (high GFR), ATP/adenosine is released → constricts the afferent arteriole → reduces glomerular hydrostatic pressure → decreases GFR back to normal; this autoregulates single-nephron GFR independently of systemic pressure changes', 'TGF activates the renin-angiotensin system when GFR is too low', 'The macula densa directly constricts the glomerular capillaries', 'B', 'TGF is a negative feedback loop: high GFR → high tubular flow → increased NaCl delivery to macula densa cells in JGA → NKCC2 transports more NaCl → macula densa cell swelling and ATP/adenosine release → adenosine A1 receptors on afferent arteriole → vasoconstriction → reduced glomerular pressure → reduced GFR, restoring flow to the macula densa. This autoregulation operates within a blood pressure range of ~80–180 mmHg independently of systemic effects.');
